children.subject: I did EE 47D and CS 170 this semester, so I've kind of partially done this, at least for the second half of the semester. I'd say that 170 problem sets can take from around 8-12 hours a week, maybe a bit less if you are able to go to HW party or OH to get help on the harder problems every week. I mostly learned from the textbook, and didn't really go to discussion, so maybe tack on an extra ~3 hours for that. Most of the work is the problem sets though - there's no coding except for the project at the end of the semester. For EE16A, I didn't have to go to discussion or lab, but I had to spend maybe 1.5 hours a week catching up on lecture/notes, and like 5 hours a week on the HW. I'd expect like 10 hours a week for 16A if you include discussion for participation and the labs, which would be more hands on than just problem sets. So that'd be a total of like ~25 hours total for both.

I took both this semester and my honest advice is to honestly just stay on top of it and don't fall behind. EE16A isn't too hard but it's a good amount of work (3 hours lecture, 2 hours discussion, 4-10 hrs HW, 2-3 hrs lab, it all adds up). CS170 was a consistent 10-15 hours a week of work. Midterm weeks were when workload got higher simply because of studying, but since there's a lot of material in both classes, staying on top of it will keep your perceived workload consistent (and therefore more manageable) in the long run.

history.content: I know this will vary depending person to person, but just wanting an estimate from people who have taken those before? approx how many hours a week should I expect to spend on those total? (and doing what kind of work, like just sitting and studying concepts vs doing problem sets, etc)
